{"author":{"id":"4bb6c1767e50694cfde61856db22bf137d1651e8a0b5ca858c486db3dd02f280"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1778536842,"nonce":"W8mWZNs+tgQIrzfh4oeFgLMMwOE=","title":"Position-weight + target_ratio sweeps (post-6-cell calibration)","message":"After the lit-replication 6-cell matrix (`f47abb1`) lands, two calibration sweeps may be needed depending on results.\n\n## Sweep A: position weight\n\nAround the 6-cell's winning configuration, sweep `effector_hold_pos = effector_pos_running ∈ {0.1, 1.0, 10.0, 100.0}`. Inspect velocity profiles to pick the natural weight; target a position-vs-control loss ratio around 10:1 (position dominant, but control nonzero enough to discriminate strategies).\n\n## Sweep B: target_ratio with `loss_update_enabled = True`\n\nAfter Sweep A picks a position weight, sweep `loss_update_ratio ∈ {0.01, 0.1, 0.5, 1.0}` with `loss_update_enabled = True`. The control weight (`nn_output`) self-tunes to maintain `J_u / J_x = target_ratio`; position weight stays fixed at Sweep A's pick.\n\nThis explores whether the runtime ratio enforcer produces qualitatively different trajectories vs the explicit-weight Sweep A.\n\n## Decision criteria\n\n- **Sweep A**: visual inspection of velocity profiles (smoothness, peak height, reach duration). Loss-component magnitudes as diagnostic. Pick weight that produces biologically-plausible reaches with non-degenerate control magnitude.\n- **Sweep B**: same visual criteria; focus on whether `loss_update` converges to a different trajectory family.\n\n## Conditional execution\n\nThis issue is deferred until the 6-cell matrix completes. If 6-cell results are clean and within expected ranges, sweeps may not be needed at all — they exist to be ready for use if calibration looks off.\n\n## References\n\n- `f47abb1`: the 6-cell matrix that triggers this.\n- `c99ad9d`: training-methods coord.\n- Existing ratio-enforcer code: `src/rlrmp/loss.py:735-810`.","files":null}]}